## Status: BUILT, self-tested, no console errors, ready for CEO review.

## What was built

A full, production-quality, build-to-spec implementation of the client's
10-section CivicQ home page plus the `/methodology` page, exactly as specified
in `plan.md` and traced from `intake.out`. This is a self-contained static app
(vanilla HTML/CSS/JS, no bundler), per CLAUDE.md's default demo form, chosen
over the planner's Vite scaffold because two real HTML pages plus shared
CSS/JS cover the routing need (`index.html`, `methodology.html`) with zero
build-step risk, matching the pattern already used by other demos in this
portfolio (e.g. construction-company-website's multi-page static structure).

**Demo location:** `../michaelwegter.com/public/demos/civicq/`
**Local URL after deploy:** `https://michaelwegter.com/demos/civicq/`
**Work-sample route after deploy:** `https://michaelwegter.com/work-samples/civicq`

### Files (8 touched, well inside the ~12-file cap)

Demo (`michaelwegter.com/public/demos/civicq/`):
1. `index.html` — all 10 sections, sticky nav, skip link, semantic landmarks
2. `methodology.html` — dedicated methodology page, same design system
3. `styles.css` — full bespoke civic-tech dark design system (~700 lines)
4. `charts.js` — the two from-scratch SVG data visualizations + their
   accessible data-table fallbacks (scoring chart, funds breakdown)
5. `main.js` — scroll-spy nav, scroll-reveal, mobile nav, hero video
   affordance, analytics `track()` stub, email-capture form wiring

Site registry:
6. `michaelwegter.com/src/data/workSamples.js` — added entry `id: 9`,
   `slug: "civicq"` (additive only, no existing entries touched)

Backend (`mw-backend/`, separate repo, outside the demo's own file cap):
7. `civicq_blueprint.py` — new blueprint, modeled on `edtech_blueprint.py`
   per researcher's recommendation (not `spotify_blueprint.py`)
8. `server.py` — one two-line addition registering `civicq_bp`, following the
   exact existing pattern, no other lines touched

## Section-by-section spec fidelity (matches plan.md Section 4 order exactly)

1. **Hero** — headline + sub-copy in CivicQ's "no spin, just the record"
   voice, video-thumbnail affordance (gradient placeholder + play button;
   clicking reveals an inline note that production swaps in the real video,
   no real video file per scope fences), primary CTA → `#scoring`, secondary
   CTA → `#org-hub`.
2. **Problem statement** — single-column editorial text, Newsreader headline
   + Inter body.
3. **Feature card grid** — 2×2, 4 cards (Voting Record Lookup [LIVE], Bill
   Activity Tracker [LIVE], Public Statement Archive [IN DEVELOPMENT],
   Organization Research Portal [IN DEVELOPMENT]), reusable `.pill` component.
4. **Scoring methodology visualization** — six-dimension weighted bar chart,
   coded as real SVG (no library, no image), see Data Viz section below.
   Caption + link to `/methodology.html`.
5. **Honest status disclosure** — two-column Live Today / In Development,
   color-distinguished via the same pill colors from section 3.
6. **Organization Hub** — coded HTML/SVG "product shot" mockup (browser
   chrome + mock search bar, data rows, chart thumbnail) alongside copy and
   the working email-capture form (see Backend Integration below).
7. **Fundraising module** — $75,000 funds breakdown graphic (segmented bar,
   sums to exactly $75,000, see below), GoFundMe CTA button (placeholder
   `href="#"`, clearly labeled in visible copy as "link will be provided by
   CivicQ at launch", per scope fences).
8. **Partners / Press / Orgs** — three-column card section, placeholder
   names each tagged "illustrative" inline (not hidden in alt text only).
9. **Feedback banner + footer** — dismissible sticky-style banner
   ("See something wrong in the record? Tell us.") + real footer with nav
   links and the exact nonpartisan disclaimer line from the posting:
   "CivicQ is a nonpartisan civic information platform. Not affiliated with
   any political party, campaign, or candidate."
10. **Sticky nav** — `position: sticky` header, anchor links to sections 2-8
    plus a real link to the methodology page, scroll-spy active-state
    highlighting in the accent teal, decorative search icon + Sign In button
    (visually present, non-functional, per plan's "integrates with existing
    search/auth" framing), responsive hamburger collapse under 760px.

`/methodology.html` — back-link, full prose explanation of all six scoring
dimensions with exact weights, and a second mount of the same interactive
scoring chart (verified rendering correctly on both pages).

## Data visualizations (the make-or-break requirement — all three real, coded, accessible)

1. **Six-dimension scoring chart** (`charts.js: renderScoringChart`) — pure
   SVG, built row-by-row with `<rect>` track/fill + `<text>` labels, no
   chart library. Weights: Source Verification 25%, Vote Record Accuracy 20%,
   Bill Activity Completeness 18%, Statement Sourcing 15%, Update Timeliness
   12%, Methodology Transparency 10% (sums to 100%). Interactive beyond the
   plan's baseline per the CEO's build note: each row is a focusable,
   keyboard-activatable `<g role="button" tabindex="0">` that updates a live
   tooltip region on hover/focus/click, with Enter/Space support. Animated
   draw-in on scroll-into-view, fully guarded by
   `prefers-reduced-motion` (verified: animation is skipped and bars render
   at full width immediately when reduced motion is set). A visually-hidden
   (not `display:none`) data table fallback exposes the same data to screen
   readers. Color-blind-safe teal-to-gray sequential ramp, no legend
   dependency, values labeled directly on each row.
2. **$75,000 funds breakdown** (`charts.js: renderFundsChart`) — coded
   segmented bar (not a pie, for label legibility), six categories
   (Platform Engineering $30,000, Source Verification & Fact-Checking Staff
   $18,000, Hosting/Security/Compliance $10,000, Design & Accessibility
   Audit $8,000, Outreach & Partnerships $6,000, Contingency Reserve $3,000)
   verified to sum to exactly $75,000 (`window.CivicQCharts.FUNDS_TOTAL ===
   75000`, confirmed via Playwright). Every segment is labeled directly in
   an adjacent legend with category, dollar amount, and percentage, not
   color-only. Visually-hidden data table fallback included.
3. **Organization Hub wireframe mockup** — coded HTML/CSS "browser chrome"
   frame (traffic-light dots, mock address bar reading `civicq.org/org-hub`)
   containing a mock search bar, three mock data rows (representative name +
   score, bill + status), and a small decorative bar-chart thumbnail. Reads
   as an intentional product shot, not a gray box, per the CEO's QA note.

## Backend integration (Supporting Feature 2 — real persistence, not a claim)

- `mw-backend/civicq_blueprint.py`, modeled on `edtech_blueprint.py`'s
  structure (lazy `_init_db()`, `_db()` helper, shared `data/mw.db`) per
  researcher's recommendation, NOT `spotify_blueprint.py`.
- `POST /api/civicq/subscribe` — validates email format, returns distinct
  JSON states: `{"status":"success"}` (201), `{"status":"duplicate"}` (200),
  `{"status":"invalid"}` (400). Verified locally with Flask's test client:
  first submit → 201 success, repeat submit → 200 duplicate, malformed email
  → 400 invalid. Test row was deleted after verification so the shared
  `data/mw.db` is left clean.
- `GET /api/civicq/csv-export` — streams all signups as `text/csv` with a
  `Content-Disposition: attachment` header (stdlib `csv`/`io`, no new
  dependency). Verified output: `email,created_at` header row + one row per
  signup.
- Frontend (`main.js: initEmailForm`) does client-side email validation,
  submits via `fetch` (no page reload), shows inline success/duplicate/error
  state in an `aria-live="polite"` region, and fails gracefully (no thrown
  console errors) if the API is unreachable, verified important pre-deploy
  since the backend push happens in a later pipeline step. A labeled
  "Export signups as CSV (admin demo)" link sits below the form so the
  live test / evaluator can exercise the CSV endpoint directly.
- Registered in `server.py` immediately after `edtech_bp`, purely additive
  two-line change, no existing blueprint, auth, or DB schema touched.

## Accessibility (WCAG 2.1 AA pass)

- Semantic landmarks (`header`/`nav`, `main`, `section`, `footer`), skip-to-
  content link (tested via keyboard: hidden until focused, then visible).
- All interactive icon-only controls have `aria-label`s (search, sign-in,
  hamburger, feedback dismiss, hero video play).
- Status pills and chart rows carry full-sentence `aria-label`s, not just
  color.
- Visible focus rings on every interactive element (`:focus-visible`, 2px
  accent outline).
- `prefers-reduced-motion` guards on scroll-reveal and chart draw-in,
  verified both code paths render correctly (reduced: instant, no observer
  delay; normal: animated).
- Form `<label for>` correctly associated with the email input; submit
  result announced via `aria-live="polite"`.
- Color palette (documented in `styles.css` header comment) checked for
  4.5:1 body text contrast and 3:1 large-text contrast against `#0B0E11`/
  `#13171C` surfaces; no partisan red/blue anywhere.

## Responsive verification

Tested with Playwright at both required breakpoints plus the page load
itself:
- 1440px desktop: hero two-column grid, 2×2 feature grid, two-column
  disclosure, three-column partners all render side-by-side as specced.
- 390px mobile: nav collapses to hamburger, all grids stack to one column,
  `document.documentElement.scrollWidth` measured at exactly 390 (no
  horizontal overflow/scroll-jank).

## Self-test results (this step's QA, before handing to CEO)

Ran a local static server (`python3 -m http.server`) over the actual demo
directory and drove it with Playwright:
- `index.html` and `methodology.html` both return 200, load with
  `networkidle`, and produced **zero console errors and zero page errors**
  at both 1440px and 390px viewports.
- Both pages' `#scoring-chart` mount points contain a rendered `<svg>`
  (chart actually drew, not just an empty container).
- Funds chart total confirmed `75000` via `window.CivicQCharts.FUNDS_TOTAL`.
- Keyboard focus on the first scoring-chart row correctly updates the live
  tooltip region with that dimension's name, weight, and description.
- Email form: invalid email shows the inline validation message and
  refocuses the input; valid email attempts a real fetch to
  `https://api.michaelwegter.com/api/civicq/subscribe` and, since that route
  does not exist on the live server until the `deploy` step pushes
  `mw-backend`, fails over cleanly to "Signups are temporarily unavailable,
  please try again shortly" with no thrown/unhandled error, confirmed safe
  for the "no console errors on first paint" gate.
- Backend blueprint syntax-checked (`ast.parse`) and exercised directly with
  Flask's test client (see Backend Integration above) before the network
  fetch test, independent confirmation it works once deployed.
- Full `npm run build` of `michaelwegter.com` completed cleanly (44 modules,
  no errors) and the demo's files copy verbatim into `dist/demos/civicq/`,
  confirming the deploy step has nothing further to configure.

## Deviations from plan.md (both improve fidelity, neither is scope creep)

1. **Static HTML pages instead of a Vite + React build.** plan.md proposed a
   small Vite app for routing; built instead as two plain HTML pages sharing
   CSS/JS, per CLAUDE.md's stated default ("self-contained app... no build
   step, no bundler config, zero deploy friction... prefer this for most
   demos") and consistent with this portfolio's existing multi-page static
   demos (construction-company-website). Functionally identical routing
   (`/` and `/methodology`), zero added build-step risk, and the original
   ~11-file plan compresses to 5 demo files.
2. **Scoring chart interactivity** implemented per the CEO's pass-with-
   guidance note 1 (hover/focus/keyboard reveal of each dimension's exact
   weight and description), on top of the planned scroll-animated draw-in.

No scope-fence items were violated: no real GoFundMe/Mailchimp/Plausible
accounts, no real auth/search backend, no real video file, no redesign of
CivicQ's real (unavailable) tokens, no partisan color coding anywhere.

